title: Postcards from London: A bus tour with Sal
text:
Sal Maiorana, who has covered the Buffalo Bills since 1990 for the Democrat and Chronicle, covered the game in London this week. Here are his daily updates of the sights he took in across the pond. Oct. 25
To say the least, this has been a great week, at least until the game started and I had to subject myself to the play of EJ Manuel. Wembley Stadium was awesome, but my lone regret is I was never here before they modernized it to the tune of about $2 billion U.S. dollars. It pretty much looks like the new stadium palaces back home.
I had a chat with one of the London writers, and he said this was by far the loudest, most knowledgeable crowd he's seen for the 13 international series games here. Way to go Bills fans. One thing I found funny: When the scoreboard prompted people to get loud when the Bills had the ball, they did so by booing rather than scream and act like lunatics like we do in the U.S.
Not sure what Wembley holds, but there's way more than 80,000 people here. pic.twitter.com/BS2U9KRkOF
— Sal Maiorana (@salmaiorana) October 25, 2015 ROCHESTER DEMOCRAT AND CHRONICLE

Oct. 24
Buy Photo We don't know what Buffalo Bills reporter Sal Maiorana gets a selfie with a pair of London bobbies. (Photo: Sal Maiorana/ staff photographer)
After a bus tour with Bills fans Friday, I decided to take the official guided London bus tour Saturday, and it was great. We had a self-admitted "history geek" as our host, and he shared some really cool facts. Did you know the great fire in 1666 that wiped out 80 percent of London was started because some dude forgot to turn his oven off one night?
I jumped off at Trafalgar Square at the foot of Regent Street to check out the NFL event there, but I showed up when the Jaguars players were on stage and missed the Bills. That's OK, I see enough of them. Interestingly, the Jags - given their long-term commitment to playing here - were really being treated as the hometown team. And yes, I even saw some Jags fans there. Wasn't sure any existed.
Sal Maiorana took a guided tour of London and here’s what he saw.
Oct. 23
In this image released by AMC, Don Draper portrayed by Jon Hamm, appears in a scene from season six of "Mad Men." (Photo: Michael Yarish, AP)
Had my birthday dinner at Prezzo, a nice Italian restaurant, and the boys bought me a piece of cake and the waitresses sang happy birthday. So afterward, an elderly couple stopped by the table to wish me happy birthday. We got to talking, and it turns out the man's name was Robert Leaf, who just happens to be one of the most iconic figures in public relations history, the real life version of Don Draper.
He was born in 1931 in Manhattan, was a Yankee fan then, but is a Mets fan now. In between switching allegiances, he attended the University of Missouri and thought about a career in sports journalism before switching to PR. "Paid better then, still does," he told me with a wink.
He went to work for a small firm called Burson-Marsteller, and when the company decided to expand overseas, Robert was the choice to head the expansion. Ultimately, it became the largest PR firm in the world, and Robert opened offices all over Europe and the Far East, as well as the first PR agency in the history of the Soviet Union. In January 2014, he was included in 'The Debrett's 500', a list of people considered to be Britain's 500 most influential people.

As birthdays go, I guess this qualifies as rather special because none of my previous 52 birthdays were ever spent out of the United States. Of course, given the time of year my birthday falls, I'm always doing something regarding the Bills and today was no different.
While they were practicing, the media took a tour of The Grove, which is where they are staying. The place is unreal. Check out my story and video Friday and you'll see. Saw Kim Pegula in the lobby. She said, "Hey Sal." We chatted. We're buddies.
So far I've stayed away from British food. Had Subway for dinner one night (don't laugh) but then found a very good Italian restaurant within walking distance from the Marriott Wednesday. Also, had an awesome chicken soup in the hotel today. Pub time Thursday for my birthday. If I'm absent tomorrow, you'll know why. Cheers to me.
My birthday dinner with the western New York media in London. pic.twitter.com/34IjI8PaZC

***
Oct. 21
Thankfully I'm not doing any driving here. I've now been to England or Scotland three times, and I still can't imagine trying to drive on the wrong side of the road. I was on the media bus today for the first hour-long trip out to the Bills practice facility, and I winced at least three or four times thinking we were about to get in a head-on crash. It's so weird.
The Bills' hotel is amazing, not that we are allowed to go in. Our on-site media room is in what is called the potting shed. Clueless as to what that means, but I'm pretty sure it was a greenhouse in a former life. Driving in, I noticed the golf course here on the property. It looks great, and it must be because I heard it's hosting the 2016 British Masters. If I could afford it, I'd play, but I can't, so I won't. Going rate right now is about 200 pounds, or $350 bucks. I'm guessing that won't fly on the expense report.

***
Oct. 20
Well, I'm here. Drove from Buffalo to Toronto Monday night and flew overnight on British Airways direct into Heathrow. Can't sleep on a plane, and didn't. So I wrote a story and watched two movies — Entourage and True Story, plus a couple episodes of Curb Your Enthusiasm. Man, great in-seat entertainment options, yet there was no Wi-Fi on this big ol' plane. Found that a bit odd.
When I arrived in London, it took a full two hours to finally get to the hotel. Half-hour going through customs, during which a couple Bills fans recognized me, which was funny, then off to find my luggage and exchange currency. From there, Heathrow Express to the Paddington Station, then a cab to the Marriott. It was 1 p.m. local time. Sleep. See ya tomorrow.
